title: For Sale:  RUSSIAN  Izhevsk M44 7.62x54R
postcontent:
RUSSIAN  Izhevsk M44's are much sought after and preferred to other Arsenals, I have 2 Russian Izhevsk dated 1945.  Arsenals date M44 production began at Izhevsk in 1943 one year before official adoption and continued through 1948. The first year of production is uncommon at an estimated 50,000 total and typically bring a premium. All other years are relatively common, but 1947 is a low production year. Tula only made M44s in 1944 and these should be considered uncommon and purchased when found at the price of a typical Izhevsk M44. 
Don't be fooled by price of the less sought after M44's from neighboring eastern block countries- this is a real Russian rifle!  These 2 have the attached folding bayonet as well!

REDACTED / Justin

Freedom Munitions "Like-New" manufacturing process provides like-new ammo performance.
FREEDOM MUNITIONS inspects all cartridge cases for defects. The Scharch Range Master machines are fully automated and cases are checked for any debris and pressure tested for any splits or cracks. Primers are removed, flash holes are cleared, and primer pockets are reamed to accept new primers.
FREEDOM MUNITIONS then washes cases in an acid wash specially designed to remove all remaining burnt powder from the flash hole and interior of the case which tumbling doesn't remove. Then cases are tumbled in a dryer for a factory look and finish.
FREEDOM MUNITIONS roll sizes all cases on our own designed machines to meet S.A.A.M.I.specification. This method is the industry standard for commercial sizing, insuring the case wall is sized down to the rim which insures new component performance.
FREEDOM MUNITIONS then loads these processed components on the same fiber optic-controlled Ammo Load machines as our premium new ammo. These are the same machines used by some of the largest manufacturers in the industry. These machines assure S.A.A.M.I. specifications for priming depth, pressure and overall cartridge length.
FREEDOM MUNITIONS "Like-New" manufacturing process with the new projectile, powder and primer assures factory ammo performance that discriminating shooters expect.

title: For Sale/Trade:  FN Five-seveN 5.7x28 Pistol & PS90 Bullpup 1650 Rounds
postcontent:
Photo album here: http://imgur.com/a/hteI6

I really love these guns, but I've been considering getting away from the 5.7 and consolidating all my firearms into the same caliber. I'm not sold on it yet, but I'd like to see what else is out there... and I could always use cash. 

The PS90 is the Gen3 trigger pack, tri-rail edition. I topped it off with an EOTech XPS holo sight and it has a side rail installed on the right side (can be mounted either side I think) with a sig laser on it. I have 5 50-round mags (3 are FN and 2 are AR57 I think). I have the original box and warranty card that has not been filled out or submitted yet... I am not sure about a manual. That might be something you have to download. The PS90 is in flawless, like new condition. I'm asking $1,500 for rifle and the 5 mags and side rail. If you want the EOTech it'll be $400 (it's brand new and has box/paperwork). Sig laser is $50.

The FN FiveseveN pistol comes with 3 20-magazines, original hardcase, manual, lock, cleaning kit... everything from the factory. As you can see from the picture, it's the two-tone FDE version. It has some slight wear on the tall front site post from a holster, but nothing major. Internals look brand new and shows no signs of wear and tear. I would like to get $1,400

As you probably know with the 5.7x28 rounds, finding them is the first problem and then finding them at a reasonable price is the second. I have 1,688 total. I'm trying to sell it as a package so I'll sell it for less than $0.60 per round. So the ammo comes out to $1,000.

If you want the whole package it totals to $4,350

I'm willing to trade for other stuff that I might be interested in but I'm interested in losing money... cash or guns must be fairly valued. I tried to do that with my stuff here... the market is crazy right now I know... but I'm indefinitely giving a break on the ammo. Feel free to make trade offers or I can let you know a rough list of stuff I want from the top of my head.

Keep in mind everything is in great shape and I rather like them both. I'm just considering keeping to the more "standard" calibers.

As a bonus, if you are into reloading, I have 5.7 LEE dyes and between 100 and 200 rounds of brass for the 5.7x28

title: For Sale/Trade:  Russian AK shotgun-Vepr 12
postcontent:
In my own humble opinion, the Vepr 12 from the Molot manufactory in Russia is the finest semi-automatic combat shotgun in existence. This is the shotgun that every Saiga 12 WANTS to be but cannot. Only 1000 have been shipped into the country as of yet--but being an AK at heart, most aftermarket accessories are still interchangeable.

With its AK heritage, you can rest assured that you can drag it through hell and back as a daily excursion and it will keep on tickin'--you cannot kill this weapon. The Vepr 12 was also designed with an auto gas regulator (unlike its little brother, the Saiga) meaning that you can reliably feed ANY 2 3/4 or 3 inch shells you can find without manual adjustment from birdshot to buckshot, low to high brass. Unlike the Saiga, the Vepr 12 was based on the RPK instead of the standard AK, which means that the receiver has a hinged dust cover, a thicker receiver, and a polymer rail on top. Also included in the design is an auto-bolt hold open and a magwell which allows for AR-15 style magazine changes instead of rock and lock.

Instead of explaining every new intricacy, watch this great video by the Military Arms Channel on youtube to get an idea of all of its features.
 http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fMfzN5LZc3o

I have added a Magpul rail to the lower handguard, as well as a vertical foregrip. Additionally, I have replaced the standard wooden stock with a sturdy clubfoot. The Vepr would come with two 10 round SGM magazines and 1 original Russian 5 round.

I've sent roughly 150 shells down the tube and I am QUITE fond of my deadly new toy. Please dont hesitate to send any questions that you may have--im sure that I didnt answer every question you might have in this ad. Im a gun enthusiast though and I am constantly buying/selling/trading so show me what you have in trade. Thanks for looking!
